          clearly extractable by Google's Gemini-powered retrieval pipeline.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 1: What Are AI Overviews -->
      <section id="what-are-ai-overviews" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>What Are Google AI Overviews?</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Google AI Overviews are AI-generated answer panels that appear at the top of Google Search results, above the traditional list of blue links.</strong>
          They provide a synthesised answer to the user's query, drawing from multiple web sources, and display source citations that users can expand to see the
          underlying pages.
        </p>

        <p>
          Google announced AI Overviews at Google I/O in May 2024 and began rolling them out in the United States at general availability. The product
          had previously run in a limited experimental form known as the Search Generative Experience (SGE) — see our companion page
          <a href="/sge-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">SGE Optimisation: Search Generative Experience Explained</a>
          for the full terminology history and how the product changed between the SGE phase and the current AI Overviews product.
        </p>

        <p>
          AI Overviews are powered by a version of Google's Gemini model working in conjunction with Google's standard web index and Knowledge Graph.
          This integration is significant: it means AI Overviews share retrieval infrastructure with traditional search, and pages that perform well
          in organic search tend to perform well in AI Overview citation as well — though the relationship is not deterministic.
        </p>

        <p>
          Not every query triggers an AI Overview. Google applies the feature selectively, prioritising queries where a synthesised answer adds value
          over a list of links. Informational queries, how-to queries, and multi-faceted questions are more likely to trigger Overviews than transactional
          queries or branded navigational queries. Query trigger rates have varied over time as Google has adjusted the feature's scope.
        </p>

        <h3>What AI Overviews Look Like</h3>

        <p>
          A typical AI Overview appears as a bordered panel at the top of the SERP. It contains a generated text answer, typically two to five paragraphs,
          accompanied by a collapsed panel showing source citations. Users can click "Show more" or expand the sources list to see which pages were cited.
          Each citation includes the page title and domain, with a link to the source page.
        </p>

        <p>
          For brands, this creates a two-level visibility opportunity: presence in the generated text (the highest-value placement) and presence in the
          source citations panel (secondary but still commercially meaningful). Optimising for both requires attention to content quality, passage-level
          clarity, and the underlying organic ranking signals that determine retrieval eligibility.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 2: How AI Overviews Are Generated -->
      <section id="how-overviews-generated" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>How Google AI Overviews Are Generated</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Google AI Overviews are generated through a multi-stage pipeline that combines live web retrieval with Gemini's language generation capabilities.</strong>
          Understanding this pipeline is the foundation of effective AI overview optimization.
        </p>

        <h3>Stage 1: Query Understanding</h3>
        <p>
          When a user submits a search query, Google's systems first determine whether the query is eligible for an AI Overview. This involves intent
          classification — distinguishing informational queries that benefit from synthesis from transactional queries where a direct answer is less
          appropriate. Complex or multi-part queries are more likely to trigger Overviews; simple navigational queries typically are not.
        </p>

        <h3>Stage 2: Web Retrieval</h3>
        <p>
          For eligible queries, Google retrieves a set of candidate pages from its standard web index. This retrieval step is not fundamentally different
          from the retrieval underlying traditional search results. Pages that rank well organically — through established signals including backlink
          authority, topical relevance, and technical health — are disproportionately represented in the retrieved candidate set.
        </p>
        <p>
          Google's Knowledge Graph also contributes at this stage, providing structured entity data that helps the system interpret the query and
          identify the most relevant entities and their relationships.
        </p>

        <h3>Stage 3: Passage Extraction and Synthesis</h3>
        <p>
          Gemini processes the retrieved pages and extracts the passages most relevant to the query. This is where content structure matters most.
          The model is looking for clean, extractable units of information — not pages as a whole, but specific passages that answer the query clearly.
          Pages with well-segmented headings, declarative statements, and self-contained paragraphs are more amenable to extraction than dense, continuous prose.
        </p>
        <p>
          The model synthesises these extracted passages into a coherent answer. Sources used in the synthesis are cited in the Overview's reference panel.
          Importantly, not every retrieved page becomes a cited source — only those from which the model actually extracts content for the generated answer.
        </p>

        <h3>Stage 4: Quality and Safety Review</h3>
        <p>
          Google applies additional quality filters before displaying an AI Overview. This includes checking for policy compliance, assessing the
          reliability of sources used, and applying heightened scrutiny to YMYL (Your Money or Your Life) query types. For health, finance, and legal
          queries, Google applies stricter sourcing standards, favouring established authoritative sources over general-purpose content sites.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 3: Signals That Influence Citation -->
      <section id="signals-that-influence-citation" class="anchor-top mb-16">
        <div class="prose-dark">
          <h2>Signals That Influence AI Overview Citation</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>No single signal guarantees AI Overview citation — it results from a combination of retrieval eligibility, content quality, and structured data clarity.</strong>
            The following signals have the strongest observable influence on citation probability, based on published research and industry observation.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-8 space-y-5">

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Traditional Organic Ranking</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Studies consistently show that pages ranking in the top 10 organic results for a query are the most frequently cited in AI Overviews
              for that same query. This is the strongest single predictor. Investing in the SEO signals that drive organic ranking — topical authority,
              quality backlinks, technical health — is the highest-leverage starting point for AI Overview optimisation.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">E-E-A-T Signals</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Experience, Expertise, Authoritativeness, and Trustworthiness. Google applies E-E-A-T evaluation to AI Overview source selection
              particularly for YMYL queries. Demonstrable E-E-A-T signals include named authors with verifiable credentials, citations from
              established publications, transparent organisational information, and consistent entity data across the web.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Structured Data and Schema Markup</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              FAQPage, HowTo, Article, and Product schema each help Google's systems understand the type and structure of your content,
              reducing ambiguity about what a page covers. Schema does not directly cause AI Overview inclusion, but it improves the
              precision with which Gemini can extract relevant passages from your pages.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Passage-Level Answer Clarity</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Pages where individual paragraphs function as standalone answers to specific questions are more extractable than pages where
              information is spread across long, interconnected paragraphs. Each major section should open with a clear declarative statement.
              The model looks for passages it can extract and reproduce accurately — give it clean, self-contained units.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Topical Depth and Comprehensiveness</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Pages that demonstrate comprehensive topical coverage — addressing the main query, related sub-questions, and adjacent concerns
              within a single well-structured document — tend to be cited more frequently than pages covering only the narrow query term.
              Topical depth is a long-standing SEO signal that translates directly into AI Overview citation probability.
            </p>
          </div>

        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 4: Content Structure for AI Overviews -->
      <section id="content-for-ai-overviews" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Content Structure for Google AI Overviews</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Content written for AI Overview citation follows the same structural principles as content written for featured snippets — but with greater emphasis on multi-passage extraction and source credibility.</strong>
        </p>

        <h3>Lead with a Declarative Statement</h3>
        <p>
          Every major section — and ideally the page itself — should open with a bold, quotable sentence that defines the concept or answers
          the implied question. AI Overviews consistently extract these opening statements as the basis for generated answers.
          "Google AI Overviews are AI-generated summaries that appear above organic results for eligible queries" is the kind of sentence
          a language model can extract, attribute, and reproduce accurately. A paragraph beginning with contextual scene-setting is not.
        </p>

        <h3>Use Descriptive Heading Hierarchies</h3>
        <p>
          H2 and H3 headings that match the questions users ask — "How does Google decide which sources to cite?" rather than
          "The Selection Process" — serve dual purposes. They help traditional SEO passage ranking and they help Gemini identify
          which section of your page answers which sub-query within a multi-faceted AI Overview.
        </p>

        <h3>Include a Structured FAQ Section</h3>
        <p>
          FAQ sections with explicit question-answer pairs are among the most reliably cited content patterns in AI Overviews.
          Mark them up with FAQPage schema. Each answer should be self-contained — readable in full without requiring the surrounding
          page context. Aim for four to eight questions covering the most common queries in your topic area.
        </p>

        <h3>Provide Specific, Attributable Claims</h3>
        <p>
          Vague generalisations — "AI search is growing" — give Google's retrieval system no reason to cite your specific page.
          Specific, attributable claims — mentioning Google's own published statements, named product launches, publicly announced
          dates, or verifiable observations — give the model a reason to extract your content as the authoritative source.
          Do not invent statistics. Cite verifiable sources for any quantitative claims, and be explicit about observational versus confirmed findings.
        </p>

        <h3>Write for Both Users and Extraction</h3>
        <p>
          Content should read naturally for human visitors while being structured for machine extraction. These goals are not in
          conflict. Clear, well-organised writing is both more readable and more extractable. Avoid dense paragraphs that
          bury the answer mid-sentence, and avoid marketing language that provides nothing extractable.
          The <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO framework</a>
          covers content architecture principles in depth.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 5: Technical Optimisation -->
      <section id="technical-optimisation" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Technical Optimisation for Google AI Overviews</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Technical signals that support traditional organic ranking also support AI Overview inclusion — but a few AI-specific technical considerations deserve attention.</strong>
        </p>

        <h3>Do Not Block Google's AI Crawlers</h3>
        <p>
          Google-Extended is the user-agent associated with Google's AI training and retrieval systems, including those that power AI Overviews.
          If your robots.txt contains a Disallow rule for <code>Google-Extended</code>, you are explicitly excluding your content from consideration
          for AI Overviews. Audit your robots.txt and ensure Google-Extended is permitted on all pages you want included.
        </p>
        <p>
          Note the distinction: blocking Google-Extended does not block Googlebot (which drives traditional organic ranking), so you may currently
          rank in blue links while being entirely absent from AI Overviews. This is a common gap found in audits.
        </p>

        <h3>Implement Core Schema Markup</h3>
        <p>
          Implement Article or TechArticle schema on content pages, FAQPage schema on pages with Q&amp;A sections, HowTo schema on
          process or instructional pages, and BreadcrumbList schema on every non-homepage URL. These schemas help Gemini classify
          your content correctly and extract the right passages for the right query types.
        </p>
        <p>
          For a full implementation guide covering schema setup, see our
          <a href="/ai-brand-visibility/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">AI brand visibility guide</a>
          which covers the structured data layer in detail.
        </p>

        <h3>Core Web Vitals and Crawl Health</h3>
        <p>
          Pages that load quickly, are crawled efficiently, and have clean URL structures are better candidates for retrieval in any
          AI pipeline that uses Google's index. Core Web Vitals are not a confirmed direct AI Overview signal, but poor page experience
          reduces organic ranking probability, which indirectly reduces AI Overview citation probability through the ranking correlation.
        </p>

        <h3>Canonical and Indexation Clarity</h3>
        <p>
          Ensure every page you want considered for AI Overviews has a correct canonical tag pointing to itself (or the preferred URL),
          is not accidentally noindexed, and is accessible to Googlebot without login requirements or JavaScript rendering delays.
          These are basic indexation hygiene items, but they are frequently the cause of unexplained AI Overview absences.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 6: Comparison Table -->
      <section id="comparison-table" class="anchor-top mb-16">
        <div class="prose-dark mb-6">
          <h2>Google AI Overviews vs Traditional Organic Rankings</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>AI Overviews and traditional organic rankings share infrastructure but serve different purposes and respond to different optimisation levers.</strong>
            The table below summarises the key distinctions.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="card overflow-hidden">
          <div class="overflow-x-auto">
            <table class="w-full text-sm">
              <thead>
